		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">C64 Direct-to-TV</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>C64 Direct-to-TV</b>, called <b>C64DTV</b> for short, is a single-<a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated circuit">chip</a> implementation of the <a href="/wiki/Commodore_64" title="Commodore 64">Commodore 64</a> computer, contained in a <a href="/wiki/Joystick" title="Joystick">joystick</a> with 30 built-in <a href="/wiki/Computer_game" title="Computer game" class="mw-redirect">games</a>. The design is similar to the <a href="/wiki/Atari" title="Atari">Atari</a> Classics 10-in-1 TV Game. The circuitry of the C64DTV was designed by <a href="/wiki/Jeri_Ellsworth" title="Jeri Ellsworth">Jeri Ellsworth</a>, a self-taught <a href="/wiki/Computer_chip" title="Computer chip" class="mw-redirect">computer chip</a> designer who had formerly designed the <a href="/wiki/C-One" title="C-One">C-One</a>.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Commodore64_DTV_mugshot-x600.jpg" class="image" title="The C64 Direct-to-TV computer-in-a-joystick unit."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Commodore64_DTV_mugshot-x600.jpg/180px-Commodore64_DTV_mugshot-x600.jpg" width="180" height="243" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Commodore64_DTV_mugshot-x600.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The C64 Direct-to-TV computer-in-a-joystick unit.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Tulip_Computers" title="Tulip Computers" class="mw-redirect">Tulip Computers</a> (which had acquired the Commodore brand name in 1997) licensed the rights to Ironstone Partners, which cooperated with DC Studios, Mammoth Toys, and <a href="/wiki/The_Toy:Lobster_Company" title="The Toy:Lobster Company">The Toy:Lobster Company</a> in the development and marketing of the unit.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/QVC" title="QVC">QVC</a> purchased the entire first production run of 250,000 units and sold 70,000 of them the first day they were offered.</p>
